'''Moisés Isaac Caicedo Corozo''' (born 2 November 2001) is an Ecuadorian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{English football updater|Chelsea}} club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and the [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador national team]]. Often considered one of the best defensive midfielders in the world, Caicedo is known for his passing and interceptions.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" />

Caicedo began his career at [[Independiente del Valle]]. In February 2021, he joined [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] for an undisclosed fee, and broke into the first team following a loan to [[K Beerschot VA|Beerschot]] in the [[Belgian Pro League]]. In August 2023, he joined Chelsea for a reported fee of £100 million, winning the [[UEFA Conference League]] in [[2024–25 UEFA Conference League|2024–25]].

A full international with 60 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for Ecuador since 2020, Caicedo was selected in the nation's squads for two [[Copa América]] tournaments and the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].

==Early life==
Born in [[Santo Domingo, Ecuador]], the youngest of 10 siblings, Caicedo would play football on the scrubland pitches of his hometown, the Mujer Trabajadora neighbourhood, where goals were marked out by piles of stones.<ref name=athletic>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4670519/2023/07/07/moises-caicedo-brighton-chelsea-he-was-made-for-the-big-clubs/ |title=Moises Caicedo's rise and rise: 'He was made for the big clubs' |first=Jack |last=Lang |date=7 July 2023 |access-date=9 July 2023 |website=theathletic.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref> As a child he met local football coach Iván Guerra, who would help Caicedo and his family by paying for his football boots, travel expenses and food.<ref name=athletic/> Given Caicedo's sensitive nature, he was nicknamed "Niño Moi" by his teammates.<ref>{{cite web |title='Niño Moi' grows up to be Chelsea's driving force |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/33799/13250043/moises-caicedo-is-chelseas-driving-force-under-enzo-maresca-gabriel-martinellis-search-for-form-at-arsenal-the-radar |date=9 November 2024 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20241108172254/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/33799/13250043/moises-caicedo-is-chelseas-driving-force-under-enzo-maresca-gabriel-martinellis-search-for-form-at-arsenal-the-radar |archive-date=8 November 2024 |first=Nick |last=Wright |work=[[Sky Sports]] |location=UK |language=en}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
Caicedo was invited to play his first organised football at the Mujer Trabajadora soccer school by Guerra, and he played there between the ages of five and twelve.<ref name=times>{{cite web |url=https://www.thetimes.com/sport/football/article/moises-caicedo-ecuador-hometown-childhood-football-brighton-ct5t552xp |title=Moisés Caicedo's Ecuador roots: 'Rocks were our goalposts' |first=Gregor |last=Robertson |date=8 August 2023 |access-date=14 August 2023 |website=The Times |url-access=subscription}}</ref> The team would often play in games across the [[Santo Domingo Canton (Ecuador)|Santo Domingo Canton]], and Caicedo earned a call-up to a regional select XI.<ref name=athletic/><ref name=times/> Initially a [[Forward (association football)|forward]], Caicedo later developed into a midfielder, and at the age of thirteen joined local side Colorados Jaipadida, an affiliate of professional club [[C.D. ESPOLI|ESPOLI]].<ref name=athletic/><ref name=times/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://lacancha.com.ec/2023/05/13/moises-caicedo-y-oscar-zambrano-salieron-del-semillero-jaipadida/ |title=Moisés Caicedo y Óscar Zambrano salieron del semillero Jaipadida |trans-title=Moisés Caicedo and Óscar Zambrano left the Jaipadida seedbed |first=Mauricio |last=Bayas |date=13 May 2023 |access-date=9 July 2023 |website=lacancha.com.ec |language=es}}</ref>

Following impressive performances with Jaipadida, he was invited to train with ESPOLI.<ref name=times/> However, following ESPOLI's relegation, the tie with Jaipadida was severed, and Caicedo was left without a direct pathway to professional football.<ref name=times/> Jaipadida director Darwin Castillo sent Caicedo to trial with professional side [[Mushuc Runa S.C.|Mushuc Runa]], but after he was unable to pay for food or board, the trial was ended after a week.<ref name=times/> A later trial with [[Barcelona S.C.|Barcelona]] in [[Guayaquil]] would also prove unsuccessful.<ref name=times/>

===Independiente del Valle===
In 2016 one of his brothers brought him to [[Ecuadorian Serie A]] side [[C.S.D. Independiente del Valle|Independiente del Valle]] for trials, which he successfully passed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elcomercio.com/deportes/independiente-caicedo-juvenil-ramirez-sangolqui.html |title=Moisés Caicedo, la nueva 'joya' que formó el Independiente del Valle |trans-title=Moisés Caicedo, the new 'jewel' that formed Independiente del Valle |first=Martha |last=Córdova |date=23 February 2020 |access-date=9 July 2023 |website=El Comercio |language=es}}</ref> Having suffered a ruptured cruciate ligament in his knee in 2017, he required a number of surgeries, and was out for a total of ten months.<ref name=athletic/> Caicedo recovered from the injury, and following his arrival at the club to manage the under-18 side in 2019, Yuri Solano stated that Caicedo's athleticism "set him apart from the rest at that time".<ref name=athletic/>

Later in 2019, Caicedo captained the Independiente del Valle youth team to the Copa Mitad del Mundo title, a youth tournament in Spain.<ref name=athletic/> Following this experience, he made his debut for the Independiente del Valle first team in a 1–0 [[Ecuadorian Serie A]] win over [[L.D.U. Quito]] on 1 October of the same year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ca.soccerway.com/matches/2019/10/01/ecuador/primera-a/independiente-jose-teran/liga-deportiva-universitaria-de-quito/2967188/ |title=Independiente del Valle vs. LDU Quito – 1 October 2019 – Soccerway |publisher=Soccerway}}</ref> First team manager at the time, [[Miguel Ángel Ramírez]], would later say that "from the first day he trained with us, he was the best player in the squad".<ref name=athletic/>

Such was his importance to the first team squad, Ramirez would have Caicedo flown back from an [[U-20 Copa Libertadores]] game in Paraguay to feature in a Serie A match against rivals L.D.U. Quito in 2020 – a game which Independiente del Valle won 3–2 – before returning to the under-20 squad to play in the [[2020 U-20 Copa Libertadores]] final, where he shone in a win over Argentine opposition [[Club Atlético River Plate|River Plate]].<ref name=athletic/>

Throughout his time at Independiente del Valle, Caicedo was mostly deployed as a "number 5", a more defensive midfielder, but would also play at [[Defender (association football)|centre-back]].<ref name=athletic/> Due to the form of Independiente's Argentine midfielder [[Cristian Pellerano]], who also occupied the defensive midfield spot, Caicedo was pushed higher up, operating as a box-to-box midfielder.<ref name=athletic/> His performances in this role drew acclaim across the continent, most notably after scoring in a 5–0 win against Brazilian side [[CR Flamengo|Flamengo]] in the 2020 edition of the [[Copa Libertadores]]; after stepping over a pass from [[Beder Caicedo]], a [[Dummy (football)|dummy]] which fooled a number of Flamengo defenders, he received the ball from a [[Gabriel Torres]] pass, before placing the ball past Flamengo goalkeeper [[César (footballer, born 1992)|César]].<ref name=athletic/>

===Brighton and Hove Albion===
====2021: Transfer and first appearances====
On 1 February 2021, Caicedo joined English side [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on a four-and-a-half-year deal, for £4 million.<ref>{{Cite web |title=TNT Sports is not available in your region |url=https://www.tntsports.co.uk/geoblocking.shtml |access-date=2025-07-14 |website=www.tntsports.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2007713/albion-complete-caicedo-signing |title=Albion complete Caicedo signing |website=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |date=1 February 2021 |access-date=1 February 2021}}</ref>
On 10 February 2021, Caicedo made his first appearance in Brighton's first-team matchday squad in Brighton's 1–0 away loss against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] in the [[2020–21 FA Cup|FA Cup]], where he was an unused substitute.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55953166 |title=Leicester City 1–0 Brighton |work=BBC Sport |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |access-date=9 April 2021}}</ref>

He made his debut for Brighton on 24 August starting in the [[2021–22 EFL Cup|EFL Cup second round]] away fixture at [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] where he set up [[Andi Zeqiri]]'s first Albion goal in the 2–0 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58239552 |title=Cardiff City 0–2 Brighton & Hove Albion: Seagulls into Carabao Cup third round – BBC Sport |work=BBC Sport |date=24 August 2021 |access-date=24 August 2021}}</ref>

====2021–2022: Loan to Beerschot====
On transfer deadline day of 31 August 2021, Caicedo joined [[K Beerschot VA|Beerschot]] of the [[Belgian First Division A|Belgium top flight]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Moises Caicedo makes loan move to Beerschot |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2240745/moises-caicedo-makes-loan-move-to-beerschot/ |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion FC |date=31 August 2021 |access-date=5 September 2021}}</ref> He scored his first goal on his seventh appearance, a 90+2-minute strike to seal all three points in the 2–0 home win over [[K.R.C. Genk|Genk]].<ref>{{cite web |title=ON COMMITMENT, ENTHIOUSIAM AND CHARACTER TO VICTORY |url=https://www.beerschot.be/nl/nieuws/op-inzet-enthiousiasme-en-karakter-naar-de-overwinning |publisher=Beerschot |date=21 November 2021 |access-date=22 November 2021}}</ref> On 12 January 2022, due to shortages of central midfielders at Brighton, Caicedo was recalled from his loan and returned to England.<ref>{{cite news |title=Moises Caicedo recalled from Beerschot |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2445392/moises-caicedo-recalled-from-beerschot |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion |date=12 January 2022 |access-date=12 January 2022}}</ref>

====2022–23: Emergence and breakthrough====
[[File:BHA_5_v_Espanyol_1_pre_season_30_07_2022_103.jpg|thumb|273x273px|Caicedo playing for Brighton in July 2022.]]
Immediately on his return to Sussex, he was included on the bench where he remained for the 1–1 home draw against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.–Crystal Palace F.C. rivalry|bitter rivals]] [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on 15 January.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59903993 |title=Brighton 1–1 Crystal Palace: Late own goal gives Brighton deserved draw – BBC Sport |work=BBC Sport |date=14 January 2022 |access-date=15 January 2022}}</ref> He made his first appearance since returning and second overall for the Albion coming on as a substitute in the 3–1 away loss at [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in the [[2021–22 FA Cup#fourth round|FA Cup fourth round]] on 5 February.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60266443 |title=Tottenham 3–1 Brighton: Harry Kane praises 'brilliant' Antonio Conte as Spurs progress in FA Cup |work=BBC Sport |date=5 February 2022 |access-date=6 February 2022}}</ref> Caicedo made his Premier League debut on 9 April, starting and assisting [[Enock Mwepu]]'s goal in the 2–1 away win over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60963800 |title=Arsenal 1–2 Brighton: Gunners boss Mikel Arteta 'concerned' by performance in home defeat |work=BBC Sport |date=9 April 2022 |access-date=9 April 2022}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the Albion on 7 May, opening the scoreline in a 4–0 win over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], with a 15th minute low 25-yard strike.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61281254 |title=Brighton 4–0 Manchester United: Big defeat ends United's Champions League hopes |work=BBC Sport |date=7 May 2022 |access-date=7 May 2022}}</ref>

Caicedo scored his first goal in the [[2022–23 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2022–23 season]] in his and Brighton's sixth match of the season on 4 September, a 5–2 home win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62704218 |title=Brighton 5–2 Leicester: Graham Potter's side maintain excellent start to Premier League season |work=BBC Sport Sport |date=4 September 2022 |access-date=4 September 2022}}</ref> During January 2023, Caicedo signed a new deal with a football agency company,{{citation needed|date=August 2023}} and on 27 January, with interest coming in from league leaders Arsenal, his agents released a statement announcing he wanted to leave Brighton in an open letter on the player's [[Instagram]] page. The letter stated that, "I am the youngest of 10 siblings from a poor upbringing in [[Santo Domingo, Ecuador|Santa Domingo]] in Ecuador. My dream always to be the most decorated player in the history of Ecuador". Furthermore, Caicedo thanked Brighton fans, saying that they would "always be in my heart".<ref>{{cite web |title=Moises Caicedo: Brighton midfielder confirms he wants to leave club |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64435218 |work=BBC Sport |date=27 January 2023 |access-date=4 February 2023}}</ref> Caicedo was linked with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Moises Caicedo: Midfielder 'focused on Brighton' amid Chelsea transfer talk |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64385913 |work=BBC Sport |date=24 January 2023 |access-date=6 June 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Monday's transfer gossip: Fernandez, Caicedo, Hincapie, Shelvey, Felix, Lindelof, Bellingham |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/64446589 |work=BBC Sport |date=30 January 2023 |access-date=6 June 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Transfer news: Liverpool interested in Caicedo |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/c6p5g85kkxno |work=BBC Sport |date=6 September 2022 |access-date=6 June 2023}}</ref>

On 30 January 2023, it was reported that Brighton had rejected a second Arsenal bid for Caicedo which was worth approximately £70m.<ref>{{cite news |title=Moises Caicedo: Brighton reject second Arsenal bid for Ecuador midfielder of about £70m |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64451710 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=10 August 2023}}</ref> Thus, with Brighton having refused to sell the Ecuadorian and with the 21-year-old in contract with the Sussex-based club until the summer of 2025, the club told Caicedo to rest until the end of the transfer window. He returned to training on 1 February and returned to action on the 4th, coming on as a substitute in the 1–0 home win over [[AFC Bournemouth]] with [[Roberto De Zerbi]] asking fans not to criticise the player.<ref>{{cite web |title=Moises Caicedo: Brighton midfielder returns to training after failed move |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64488157 |work=BBC Sport |date=1 February 2023 |access-date=4 February 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Moises Caicedo: Brighton fans should not 'criticise' midfielder – Roberto de Zerbi |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64515947 |work=BBC Sport |date=3 February 2023 |access-date=4 February 2023}}</ref> On 3 March 2023, Caicedo signed a new long term contract with Brighton until 2027, with the option for another year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3092201/moises-caicedo-signs-new-long-term-contract |title=Moises Caicedo signs new long-term contract |date=3 March 2023 |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion |access-date=3 March 2023}}</ref> At Brighton's end of season awards Caicedo won both Player of the Season and Player's Player, promising that "When I go back to my flat I will give this award to my mother and father, they are my inspiration."<ref name="Awards">{{cite web |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3613149/caicedo-is-double-award-winner |title=Caicedo is double award winner |website=Brighton & Hove Albion |date=2 August 2023 |access-date=7 August 2023}}</ref>

On 27 June 2023, it was reported that Brighton had rejected a bid from Chelsea worth £80m for Caicedo.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66330292 |title=Moises Caicedo: Brighton reject Chelsea's £80m bid for midfielder |website=BBC Sport |date=10 August 2023}}</ref> On 21 July 2023, de Zerbi stated that he would "start the next season with Caicedo in… [his] head in the first 11."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66275358 |title=Moises Caicedo: Brighton plan for stay amid Chelsea interest |website=BBC Sport |date=10 August 2023}}</ref> On 10 August 2023, it was reported that [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] had agreed a £111m fee with Brighton for Caicedo,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66470820 |title=Moises Caicedo: Liverpool agree £111m fee with Brighton for Ecuador midfielder |website=BBC Sport |date=10 August 2023}}</ref> which was confirmed by Liverpool manager [[Jürgen Klopp]] a day later.<ref>{{Cite web |date=11 August 2023 |title=Sources: Caicedo wants Chelsea over Liverpool |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/38171288/jurgen-klopp-confirms-liverpool-agree-deal-brightons-moises-caicedo |access-date=2023-08-12 |publisher=ESPN |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Caicedo deal has been agreed with Brighton – Klopp |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/av/football/66463525 |access-date=2023-08-12}}</ref> However, on 12 August 2023, it was reported that Chelsea had agreed to a higher bid for Caicedo, offering a £115m fee to Brighton, inclusive of add-ons.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Law |first1=Matt |last2=Wallace |first2=Sam |date=12 August 2023 |title=Chelsea set to sign Moises Caicedo in record £115m deal to hijack Liverpool bid |language=en-GB |work=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2023/08/12/chelsea-set-sign-moises-caicedo-record-115m-deal-liverpool/ |access-date=2023-08-12 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Joyce |first1=Paul |first2=Tom |last2=Roddy |date=12 August 2023 |title=Chelsea on the brink of £115m deal for Moisés Caicedo |newspaper=[[The Times]] |language=en |url=https://www.thetimes.com/sport/football/article/chelsea-on-the-brink-of-115m-deal-for-moises-caicedo-h3wnxwrjd |access-date=2025-09-28 |issn=0140-0460}}</ref>[[File:Moisés Caicedo 20042025 (1).jpg|thumb|Caicedo with Chelsea in April 2025.|216x216px]]

===Chelsea===
====2023–24 season====
Caicedo joined Chelsea on 14 August 2023, signing an eight-year contract, with the option of a one-year extension.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Chelsea complete Moises Caicedo signing |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/chelsea-complete-moises-caicedo-signing |date=14 August 2023 |access-date=14 August 2023 |publisher=Chelsea F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Moises Caicedo completes Chelsea move |url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3634071/moises-caicedo-completes-chelsea-move |date=14 August 2023 |access-date=14 August 2023 |publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.}}</ref> Although the fee was officially undisclosed, it was reported to be worth a base transfer fee £100&nbsp;million. This fee could potentially increase to approximately £115&nbsp;million due to performance related add-ons, a [[Progression of the British football transfer fee record|British transfer fee record]] for a single player, which would surpass the £107&nbsp;million fee paid by Chelsea for [[Enzo Fernández]].<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Ornstein |first1=David |last2=Johnson |first2=Simon |date=14 August 2023 |title=Chelsea reach £115m Moises Caicedo transfer agreement with Brighton |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4764866/2023/08/13/chelsea-moises-caicedo-transfer-latest/ |access-date=14 August 2023 |publisher=[[The Athletic]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Steinberg |first1=Jacob |date=14 August 2023 |title=Chelsea complete Moisés Caicedo signing in British record £115m deal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/14/chelsea-sign-moises-caicedo-british-record-115m-deal-brighton |access-date=14 August 2023 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Caicedo received the squad number 25, which was not officially [[List of retired numbers in association football|retired]] but had not been worn since [[Gianfranco Zola]] left Chelsea in 2003; Zola endorsed Caicedo's wearing of the number.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Simon |title=Caicedo gets Zola's blessing to wear No 25 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/transfer-news-live-latest-updates/L1oM7fPGRw25/zkU1pi2zHJ18/ |access-date=10 July 2025 |work=The Athletic |date=16 August 2023}}</ref>

On 20 August, Caicedo made his debut for his new club, coming on as a substitute in the 61st minute in a [[Premier League]] match against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], which saw Caicedo give away a penalty which was converted by [[Lucas Paquetá]], in a 3–1 loss.<ref>{{Cite news |title=West Ham 3–1 Chelsea |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66490161 |access-date=2023-08-20}}</ref> On 19 May 2024, the final match day of the [[2023–24 Premier League|Premier League season]], he scored his first goal for Chelsea with a shot from 50 yards out, in a 2–1 win over Bournemouth.<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 May 2024 |title=Chelsea 2–1 Bournemouth |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/ck5k5l8x0npt |access-date=19 May 2024 |work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref>

====2024–25 season====
On 22 August 2024, Caicedo captained Chelsea for the first time against [[Servette FC|Servette]] during the [[2024–25 UEFA Conference League qualifying phase and play-off round (Main Path)|2024–25 UEFA Conference League play-off round]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Captain Caicedo on first-leg success |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/captain-caicedo-on-first-leg-success |access-date=2024-08-23 |website= |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=22 August 2024 |title=Chelsea 2–0 Servette: Caicedo entrusted with captain's armband |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c0qe7nw94vpo |access-date=2024-08-23 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 3 November 2024, he netted his first goal of the season with a volley from the edge of the 18-yard box in a 1–1 draw in an away match against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/704378 |title=Man United held by Chelsea at Old Trafford after Caicedo goal |publisher=ESPN |date=3 November 2024}}</ref> On 28 May 2025, he scored a stoppage-time goal in a 4–1 victory over [[Real Betis]] in the [[2025 UEFA Conference League final]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Begley |first=Emlyn |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/crk2zx2e1xet |title=Real Betis 1–4 Chelsea |work=BBC Sport |date=28 May 2025}}</ref> Following the conclusion of the 2024–25 season, Caicedo would be rewarded for his extraordinary performances with the Chelsea Player of the Season award.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Moises Caicedo: 'I told myself this would be my season' |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/moises-caicedo-i-told-myself-this-would-be-my-season |access-date=2025-06-11 |website=www.chelseafc.com |language=en-gb}}</ref> He was the only Chelsea player in the current squad to have started all 38 Premier League fixtures across the season.<ref>{{Cite web |last=read |first=The Chelsea News·2 min |date=2025-05-31 |title="Talks to start soon" – Fabrizio Romano shares big Chelsea news |url=https://ca.sports.yahoo.com/news/talks-start-soon-fabrizio-romano-081500415.html |access-date=2025-06-11 |website=Yahoo Sports |language=en-US}}</ref>

====2025–26 season====
On 22 August 2025, Caicedo made his 100th appearance for Chelsea, scoring in a 5–1 victory over rivals West Ham United.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Moises Caicedo marks 100th Chelsea appearance in style! |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/moises-caicedo-marks-100th-chelsea-appearance-in-style |access-date=2025-08-22 |website= |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |language=en-gb}}</ref> Later that year, on 22 October, he scored his first [[UEFA Champions League]] goal in a 5–1 victory over [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/match-report-chelsea-5-1-ajax |title=Match Report: Chelsea 5-1 Ajax |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |date=22 October 2025 }}</ref> On 17 April 2026, Caicedo signed a two-year contract extension with Chelsea, keeping him at the club until 2033.<ref>{{cite news |title=Moises Caicedo signs new Chelsea contract! |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/moises-caicedo-signs-new-chelsea-contract |access-date=17 April 2026 |publisher=Chelsea FC |date=17 April 2026}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Caicedo usually plays on the right side of a midfield pivot as a holding midfielder. His attributes are more defensive minded, but despite a more defensive role in the side, he is able to play box-to-box and contribute to his side's counterattacks. He is also a good passer while intercepting attacks along the midfield.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Moisés Caicedo's style of play: what Chelsea can expect |url=https://www.coachesvoice.com/cv/moises-caicedo-style-of-play-position-chelsea-brighton/ |access-date=2024-05-01 |website=The Coaches' Voice |language=en-GB}}</ref> Throughout 2025, Caicedo was often ranked among the best defensive midfielders in the world.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |date=2025-07-18 |title=The 25 Best Defensive Midfielders in World Soccer—Ranked |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/the-best-defensive-midfielders-in-world-soccer-ranked |access-date=2025-08-15 |website=SI |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last1=Chicken |first1=Mark White Contributions from Steven |last2=Gennery |first2=Ewan |last3=Holt |first3=Matthew |last4=published |first4=Joe Mewis |date=2025-06-16 |title=Ranked! The 10 best defensive midfielders in the world |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/ranked-best-defensive-midfielders-in-the-world |access-date=2025-08-15 |website=FourFourTwo |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite web |date=2025-08-01 |title=Who are the best midfielders in the world? Football's top |url=https://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/real-madrid/feature/who-are-the-best-midfielders-in-the-world-footballs-top-central-stars-ranked_577801.html |access-date=2025-08-15 |website=Sports Mole}}</ref>

==International career==
On 9 October 2020, Caicedo debuted for the [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador senior squad]] in a 1–0 [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]] loss to [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Moisés Caicedo, el "niño" que ya es líder de la selección de Ecuador |url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/copa-america/nota/_/id/13807354/moises-caicedo-el-nino-que-ya-es-lider-de-la-seleccion-de-ecuador |website=[[ESPN Deportes]] |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=20 June 2024 |access-date=7 October 2024 |language=es}}</ref> The same year on 13 October, he scored his first goal in a 4–2 home victory against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] at [[Estadio Rodrigo Paz Delgado]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Centro "venenoso" que sufrió Uruguay: Marcos Caicedo abrió el marcador para Ecuador |url=https://rpp.pe/futbol/eliminatorias/ecuador-vs-uruguay-moises-caicedo-y-el-gol-de-cabeza-para-abrir-el-marcador-en-el-estadio-casablanca-video-noticia-1298308 |website=[[Radio Programas del Perú]] |date=13 October 2020 |access-date=7 October 2024 |language=es}}</ref>

On 14 November, Caicedo was named in Ecuador's 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] alongside Brighton teammates [[Pervis Estupiñán]] and [[Jeremy Sarmiento]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/mundial/nota/_/id/11228629/ecuador-lista-convocados-qatar-2022-mundial-copa-mundo |title=Ecuador, el último en entregar la lista de los 26 jugadores convocados para la Copa del Mundo de Qatar 2022 |trans-title=Ecuador, the last to deliver the list of the 26 players summoned for the Qatar World Cup 2022 |website=ESPN Deportes |publisher=ESPN |date=14 November 2022 |access-date=15 November 2022 |language=es}}</ref> In the last [[2022 FIFA World Cup Group A|group match]] tie against [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] on 29 November, Caicedo scored the equaliser that would've seen Ecuador through to the round of 16. However, [[Kalidou Koulibaly]] scored for Senegal three minutes later to regain the lead and send the Senegalese through instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63711991 |title=World Cup 2022: Ecuador 1–2 Sengal – Ismaila Sarr & Kalidou Koulibaly put Africans into last 16 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=29 November 2022 |access-date=30 November 2022}}</ref>

Caicedo was called up to the final 26-man Ecuador squad for the [[2024 Copa América]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eluniverso.com/deportes/futbol/ecuador-presenta-lista-oficial-para-la-copa-america-gonzalo-plata-y-robert-arboleda-quedaron-relegados-nota/ |title=Ecuador presenta lista oficial para la Copa América: Gonzalo Plata y Robert Arboleda quedaron relegados |trans-title=Ecuador presents official roster for Copa America: Gonzalo Plata and Robert Arboleda left off the list |publisher=[[El Universo]] |date=29 May 2024 |language=es}}</ref>

